UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2114
1 AN ACT relating to education and declaring an emergency.
2 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 Section 1. KRS 158.070 is amended to read as follows:
4 (1) As used in this section:
5 (a) "Election" has the same meaning as in KRS 121.015;
6 (b) "Minimum school term" or "school term" means not less than one hundred
7 eighty-five (185) days composed of the student attendance days, teacher
8 professional days, and holidays;
9 (c) "School calendar" means the document adopted by a local board of education
10 that establishes the minimum school term, student instructional year or
11 variable student instructional year, and days that school will not be in session;
12 (d) "School district calendar committee" means a committee that includes at least
13 the following:
14 1. One (1) school district principal;
15 2. One (1) school district office administrator other than the
16 superintendent;
17 3. One (1) member of the local board of education;
18 4. Two (2) parents of students attending a school in the district;
19 5. One (1) school district elementary school teacher;
20 6. One (1) school district middle or high school teacher;
21 7. Two (2) school district classified employees; and
22 8. Two (2) community members from the local chamber of commerce,
23 business community, or tourism commission;
24 (e) "Student attendance day" means any day that students are scheduled to be at
25 school to receive instruction, and encompasses the designated start and
26 dismissal time;
27 (f) "Student instructional year" means at least one thousand sixty-two (1,062)
Page 1 of 12
XXXX 2/11/2026 4:54 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2114
1 hours of instructional time for students delivered on not less than one hundred
2 seventy (170) student attendance days;
3 (g) "Teacher professional day" means any day teachers are required to report to
4 work as determined by a local board of education, with or without the
5 presence of students; and
6 (h) "Variable student instructional year" means at least one thousand sixty-two
7 (1,062) hours of instructional time delivered on the number of student
8 attendance days adopted by a local board of education which shall be
9 considered proportionally equivalent to one hundred seventy (170) student
10 attendance days and calendar days for the purposes of a student instructional
11 year, employment contracts that are based on the school term, service credit
12 under KRS 161.500, and funding under KRS 157.350.
13 (2) (a) The local board of education, upon recommendation of the local school
14 district superintendent, shall annually appoint a school district calendar
15 committee to review, develop, and recommend school calendar options.
16 (b) The school district calendar committee, after seeking feedback from school
17 district employees, parents, and community members, shall recommend
18 school calendar options to the local school district superintendent for
19 presentation to the local board of education. The committee's
20 recommendations shall comply with state laws and regulations and consider
21 the economic impact of the school calendar on the community and the state.
22 (c) Prior to adopting a school calendar, the local board of education shall hear for
23 discussion the school district calendar committee's recommendations and the
24 recommendation of the superintendent at a meeting of the local board of
25 education.
26 (d) During a subsequent meeting of the local board of education, the local board
27 shall adopt a school calendar for the upcoming school year that establishes the
Page 2 of 12
XXXX 2/11/2026 4:54 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2114
1 opening and closing dates of the school term, beginning and ending dates of
2 each school month, student attendance days, and days on which schools shall
3 be dismissed. The local board may schedule days for breaks in the school
4 calendar that shall not be counted as a part of the minimum school term.
5 (e) For local board of education meetings described in paragraphs (c) and (d) of
6 this subsection, if the meeting is a regular meeting, notice shall be given to
7 media outlets that have requests on file to be notified of special meetings
8 stating the date of the regular meeting and that one (1) of the items to be
9 considered in the regular meeting will be the school calendar. The notice shall
10 be sent at least twenty-four (24) hours before the regular meeting. This
11 requirement shall not be deemed to make any requirements or limitations
12 relating to special meetings applicable to the regular meeting.
13 (f) A local school board of education that adopts a school calendar with the first
14 student attendance day in the school term starting no earlier than the Monday
15 closest to August 26 may use a variable student instructional year. Districts
16 may set the length of individual student attendance days in a variable student
17 instructional schedule, but no student attendance day shall contain more than
18 seven (7) hours of instructional time unless the district submitted and received
19 approval from the commissioner of education for an innovative alternative
20 calendar.
21 (3) (a) Each local board of education shall use four (4) days of the minimum school
22 term for professional development and collegial planning activities for the
23 professional staff without the presence of students pursuant to the
24 requirements of KRS 156.095. At the discretion of the superintendent, one (1)
25 day of professional development may be used for district-wide activities and
26 for training that is mandated by federal or state law. The use of three (3) days
27 shall be planned by each school council, except that the district is encouraged
Page 3 of 12
XXXX 2/11/2026 4:54 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2114
1 to provide technical assistance and leadership to school councils to maximize
2 existing resources and to encourage shared planning.
3 (b) 1. A local board may approve a school's flexible professional development
4 plan that permits teachers or other certified personnel within a school to
5 participate in professional development activities outside the days
6 scheduled in the school calendar or the regularly scheduled hours in the
7 school work day and receive credit towards the four (4) day professional
8 development requirement within the minimum one hundred eighty-five
9 (185) days that a teacher shall be employed.
10 2. A flexible schedule option shall be reflected in the school's professional
11 development component within the school improvement plan and
12 approved by the local board. Credit for approved professional
13 development activities may be accumulated in periods of time other than
14 full day segments.
15 3. No teacher or administrator shall be permitted to count participation in a
16 professional development activity under the flexible schedule option
17 unless the activity is related to the teacher's classroom assignment and
18 content area, or the administrator's job requirements, or is required by
19 the school improvement plan, or is tied to the teacher's or the
20 administrator's individual growth plan. The supervisor shall give prior
21 approval and shall monitor compliance with the requirements of this
22 paragraph. In the case of teachers, a professional development
23 committee or the school council by council policy may be responsible
24 for reviewing requests for approval.
25 (c) The local board of each school district may use up to a maximum of four (4)
26 days of the minimum school term for holidays; provided, however, any
27 holiday which occurs on Saturday may be observed on the preceding Friday.
Page 4 of 12
XXXX 2/11/2026 4:54 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2114
1 (d) Each local board may use two (2) days for planning activities without the
2 presence of students.
3 (e) Each local board may close schools for the number of days deemed necessary
4 for:
5 1. National or state emergency or mourning when proclaimed by the
6 President of the United States or the Governor of the Commonwealth of
7 Kentucky;
8 2. Local emergency which would endanger the health or safety of children;
9 and
10 3. Mourning when so designated by the local board of education and
11 approved by the Kentucky Board of Education upon recommendation of
12 the commissioner of education.
13 (4) (a) The Kentucky Board of Education, upon recommendation of the
14 commissioner of education, shall adopt administrative regulations governing
15 the use of student attendance days as a result of a local emergency, as
16 described in subsection (3)(e)2. of this section, and regulations setting forth
17 the guidelines and procedures to be observed for the approval of waivers from
18 the requirements of a student instructional year in subsection (1)(f) of this
19 section for districts that wish to adopt innovative instructional calendars, or
20 for circumstances that would create extreme hardship.
21 (b) If a local board of education determines it is necessary to amend[amends] its
22 school calendar after its adoption[ due to an emergency], the local board of
23 education[it] may lengthen or shorten any remaining student attendance days
24 by thirty (30) minutes or more, as it deems necessary, provided the amended
25 calendar provides at least one thousand sixty-two (1,062) hours of
26 instructional time for students delivered on the amended number of student
27 attendance days adopted by the local board of education[complies with the
Page 5 of 12
