UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2114
1 compliance with administrative regulations promulgated by the Kentucky Board of
2 Education.
3 (9) The Kentucky Board of Education shall promulgate administrative regulations to
4 prescribe the conditions and procedures for districts to be approved for the
5 nontraditional instruction program. Administrative regulations promulgated by the
6 board under this section shall specify:
7 (a) The application, plan review, approval, and amendment process;
8 (b) Reporting requirements for districts approved for the program, which may
9 include but are not limited to examples of student work, lesson plans, teacher
10 work logs, and student and teacher participation on nontraditional instruction
11 days. Documentation to support the use of nontraditional instruction days
12 shall include clear evidence of learning continuation;
13 (c) Timelines for initial approval as a nontraditional instruction district, length of
14 approval, the renewal process, and ongoing evaluative procedures required of
15 the district;
16 (d) Reporting and oversight responsibilities of the district and the Kentucky
17 Department of Education, including the documentation required to show clear
18 evidence of learning continuation during nontraditional instruction days; and
19 (e) Other components deemed necessary to implement this section.
20 (10) Notwithstanding the provisions of KRS 158.060(4) and the provisions of subsection
21 (2) of this section, a school district shall arrange bus schedules so that all buses
22 arrive in sufficient time to provide breakfast prior to the beginning of the student
23 attendance day. The superintendent of a school district that participates in the
24 Federal School Breakfast Program may also authorize up to fifteen (15) minutes of
25 the student attendance day to provide the opportunity for children to eat breakfast
26 during instructional time.
27 (11) Notwithstanding any other statute to the contrary, the following provisions shall
Page 9 of 12
XXXX 2/11/2026 4:54 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2114
1 apply to a school district that misses student attendance days due to emergencies,
2 including weather-related emergencies, or amends the school district's school
3 calendar after the school calendar's adoption pursuant to subsection (4)(b) of this
4 section:
5 (a) A certified school employee shall be considered to have fulfilled the
6 minimum one hundred eighty-five (185) day contract with a school district
7 under KRS 157.350 and shall be given credit for the purpose of calculating
8 service credit for retirement under KRS 161.500 for certified school personnel
9 if:
10 1. State and local requirements under this section are met regarding the
11 equivalent of the number and length of student attendance days, teacher
12 professional days, professional development days, holidays, and days
13 for planning activities without the presence of students; and
14 2. The provisions of the district's school calendar to make up student
15 attendance days missed due to any emergency, as approved by the
16 Kentucky Department of Education when required, including but not
17 limited to a provision for additional instructional time per day, are met.
18 (b) Additional time worked by a classified school employee shall be considered
19 as equivalent time to be applied toward the employee's contract and
20 calculation of service credit for classified employees under KRS 78.615 if:
21 1. The employee works for a school district with a school calendar
22 approved by the Kentucky Department of Education that contains a
23 provision that additional instructional time per day shall be used to make
24 up full days missed due to an emergency;
25 2. The employee's contract requires a minimum six (6) hour work day; and
26 3. The employee's job responsibilities and work day are extended when the
27 instructional time is extended for the purposes of making up time.
Page 10 of 12
XXXX 2/11/2026 4:54 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2114
1 (c) Classified employees who are regularly scheduled to work less than six (6)
2 hours per day and who do not have additional work responsibilities as a result
3 of lengthened student attendance days shall be excluded from the provisions
4 of this subsection. These employees may be assigned additional work
5 responsibilities to make up service credit under KRS 78.615 that would be
6 lost due to lengthened student attendance days.
7 Section 2. (1) For the 2025-2026 school year, a school district may revise its
8 school calendar in accordance with the requirements of this section.
9 (2) For purposes of this section, notwithstanding the requirement in KRS 158.070
10 that the student instructional year not be less than 170 student attendance days and any
11 other statute or administrative regulation to the contrary, students shall receive a
12 minimum of 1,062 instructional hours, less any waiver of instructional time provided in
13 accordance with KRS 158.070(3)(e) and 702 KAR 7:140.
14 (3) Notwithstanding KRS 158.070(4)(b), if a school district used all 10 available
15 nontraditional instruction days during the 2025-2026 school year, the school district may
16 reach the required instructional hours by adding time to student attendance days. A day
17 shall not exceed seven hours of instructional time unless the district submitted and
18 received approval from the commissioner of education for an innovative alternative
19 calendar.
20 (4) If a local school district is unable to provide the required 1,062 hours of
21 instruction by June 10, 2026, the commissioner of education may waive up to five student
22 attendance days. The commissioner of education shall not waive instructional days for a
23 district that did not make up days by adding time to the student instructional day.
24 Notwithstanding any other statute or administrative regulation to the contrary, student
25 attendance days waived under this subsection shall be applied on a district-wide basis.
26 (5) If a local board of education seeks to revise its school calendar under this
27 section, the board shall submit a plan for approval to the Kentucky Department of
Page 11 of 12
XXXX 2/11/2026 4:54 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2114
1 Education demonstrating how the required instructional hours will be completed.
2 (6) Notwithstanding any other statute, administrative regulation, or local board of
3 education policy to the contrary, each classified and certified employee of a local board
4 of education shall be considered to have completed one day of his or her employment
5 contract for each day made up in accordance with subsection (3) of this section and days
6 waived in accordance with subsection (4) of this section.
7 (7) If a local board of education used 10 or fewer nontraditional instruction days
8 during the 2025-2026 school year and chooses not to take advantage of subsection (4) of
9 this section for the 2025-2026 school year, the school district's average daily attendance
10 shall be calculated by deducting five low attendance days in addition to the five days
11 deducted under KRS 157.320(2).
12 Section 3. Whereas support and relief for school districts and the students
13 enrolled therein is imperative, an emergency is declared to exist, and Section 2 of this Act
14 takes effect upon its passage and approval by the Governor or upon its otherwise
15 becoming a law and Section 1 of this Act takes effect July 1, 2026.
